{{coord|26|27|43.01|N|127|49|51.8|E|region:JP|display=title}} {{Infobox Institute |name = Okinawa Institute of Science and Technology Graduate University |image= OIST logo.png |established = 1 November 2011 |head_label = President |president = [[Peter Gruss]] |faculty = 61 |staff = 813 |budget = {{JPY|19.8 billion}} |endowment = |debt = |location = [[Onna, Okinawa|Onna]], [[Okinawa Prefecture|Okinawa]], [[Japan]] |address = |website = {{official website|www.oist.jp}} }} [[File:Aerial View of Campus Buildings (26348429827).jpg|thumb|Aerial view of the OIST campus]] The {{Nihongo|'''Okinawa Institute of Science and Technology Graduate University'''|Ê≤ñÁ∏ÑÁßëÂ≠¶ÊäÄË°ìÂ§ßÂ≠¶Èô¢Â§ßÂ≠¶|Okinawa Kagaku Gijutsu Daigakuin Daigaku|'''OIST'''}} is an interdisciplinary graduate school located in [[Onna, Okinawa|Onna]], [[Okinawa Prefecture]], [[Japan]]. The school offers a 5-year [[PhD]] program in Science. Over half of the faculty and students are recruited from outside Japan, and all education and research is conducted entirely in English.
OIST relies on public subsidies paid by the Japanese government.<ref>{{Cite journal|first=D|last=Cyranoski |url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v474/n7353/full/474541b.html |title=Made in Japan |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]|publisher=Nature Publishing Group|pages=541‚Äì542|doi=10.1038/474541b|volume=474 |issue=7353 |date=29 June 2011|accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref> The government subsidy for OIST comes in two areas: a subsidy for operations and a subsidy for facilities.
==Graduate school== The [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] program is taught entirely in English and is individually tailored to each student. Students are encouraged to focus their research on cross-disciplinary areas of studies.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Degree structure|url=https://admissions.oist.jp/degree-structure|publisher=oist.jp}}</ref>
===History=== In June 2001 [[K≈çji Omi]], former Minister of State for Okinawa and Northern Territories Affairs and former Minister of State for Science and Technology Policy, announced plans to establish a new graduate university in Okinawa. A Board of Governors was appointed in 2004 and the following year, the [[National Diet|Diet]] recognized OIST as an "Independent Administrative Institution".<ref>{{citeweb|title=About ‚Äî History|url=https://www.oist.jp/history|publisher=oist.jp}}</ref> The first batch of students were welcomed in September 2012 after receiving approval.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Normile|first1=Dennis|title=Japan's New Okinawa Institute Officially Becomes Graduate University|journal=Science|date=28 October 2011|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2011/10/japans-new-okinawa-institute-officially-becomes-graduate-university|language=en}}</ref>
==Research== The research community consists of faculty and researchers divided into "units" based on area of study.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Research Overview|url=https://www.oist.jp/research-overview|publisher=oist.jp}}</ref> The university has no departments‚ÄîOIST researchers conduct multi-disciplinary research in Physics, Chemistry, Neuroscience,<ref name=economist2>{{cite news|title= Robocopulation|url=https://www.economist.com/news/science-and-technology/21601230-using-robots-model-evolutionary-conundrum-robocopulation|work=[[The Economist]]|accessdate=19 May 2014|date=26 April 2014}}</ref> Marine Science, Environmental and Ecological Sciences, Mathematical and Computational Sciences, and Molecular, Cellular, and Developmental Biology.<ref name=economist>{{cite news|title=Where rats and robots play|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21540228|work=[[The Economist]]|accessdate=15 December 2011|date=26 November 2011}}</ref>
